As you can see the above code has all been explained with the commented out lines (//Commented out line), But i will explain
the important bits of information before moving on anyway.

Alright so let us explain the important bits of information. (I will not explain anything that is self-explanatory,
feel free to post if you do not understand).
[hr]
[code]
	if (receivedPlayerName != null
				&& server.playerHandler.isPlayerOn(receivedPlayerName) == true
				&& c.reportTimer == 0 && receivedPlayerName != c.playerName) {
			System.out.println("[Server Report]: " + c.playerName
					+ " reported " + receivedPlayerName);

		}[/code]

This code snippet here is basically printing off a report onto the command prompt,
this will provide the detail of the player name who was reported, and who he was reported by in this format:
"[Server Report]: Player1 reported Player2".

For the second part I will use only one example as there are 12 possible outcomes, explaining one will be sufficient
for understanding the others.

[code]
	// Rule 1: Offensive Language
		case 0:

			if (server.playerHandler.isPlayerOn(receivedPlayerName) == false
					|| c.playerName == receivedPlayerName) {
				c.sM("That player isn't online.");
			} else if (receivedPlayerName != null
					&& server.playerHandler.isPlayerOn(receivedPlayerName) == true
					&& c.reportTimer == 0 && receivedPlayerName != c.playerName) {
				report(receivedPlayerName + " Got reported by " + c.playerName
						+ " for Offensive language");
				c.sM("Thank you for reporting " + receivedPlayerName
						+ " to our staff.");
				c.reportTimer = 120;
			} else if (c.reportTimer != 0) {
				c.sM("You must wait " + timer
						+ " seconds before reporting another user.");
			}
			break;[/code]

What this code snippet is is basically Rule 1: Offensive Language, if a player has reported somebody for a certain
rule, in this case Rule 1, a message will be sent to a staff (The Report.txt file) in this format; "Player1 has been reported by
Player2 for Offensive language.", however this message will not be sent if the player you are reporting is offline,
and it has a built in timer that will not allow you to report somebody for a number of seconds.

There is a use of "if-else" statements or "Else-if" statements as they are shown in this, saying that to avoid confusion,
these are implemented for doing various actions, for example if the player is not online who you are trying to report,
a message will be printed saying; "That player isn't online", then there is the reporting message which was explained above,
then there is the message saying; "You must wait 120 seconds before reporting another user".

The "Player isn't online statement is shown here;

[code]
	if (server.playerHandler.isPlayerOn(receivedPlayerName) == false
					|| c.playerName == receivedPlayerName) {
				c.sM("That player isn't online.");[/code]

The actual reporting of the player is shown here;

[code]
	} else if (receivedPlayerName != null
					&& server.playerHandler.isPlayerOn(receivedPlayerName) == true
					&& c.reportTimer == 0 && receivedPlayerName != c.playerName) {
				report(receivedPlayerName + " Got reported by " + c.playerName
						+ " for Offensive language");
				c.sM("Thank you for reporting " + receivedPlayerName
						+ " to our staff.");
				c.reportTimer = 120;[/code]

In the above code this uses two main variables called the "receivedPlayerName", and the "playerName" variable,
these are both used to identify both users, the "receivedPlayerName" variable is to print the player who was reported,
while "playerName" is used to show the person who reported the user. Another variable that is used is "reportTimer",
at the end of the report this variable sets the time to 120 seconds before you may report again.

The "You must wait 120 seconds before reporting another user" is shown here;

[code]
	} else if (c.reportTimer != 0) {
				c.sM("You must wait " + timer
						+ " seconds before reporting another user.");
			}
			break;[/code]

This part tells you the seconds before you may report a user again, it uses the timer variable
to do so, this variable is under the name of; "timer", as shown in the message.

The final part of this prints off to the run.bat saying; "Player1 reported player2 on date at time".
The report then is saved to a file you must make yourself called Reports.txt in the file called "Data".
The code that does all this is;

[code]
	void report(String msg) {

		BufferedWriter bw = null;

		try {
			bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("./reports/Reports.txt",
					true));
			bw.write(msg + " | On " + date + " At " + time);
			bw.newLine();
			bw.newLine();
			bw.flush();
		} catch (IOException ioe) {
			ioe.printStackTrace();
		} finally {
			if (bw != null)
				try {
					bw.close();
				} catch (IOException ioe2) {
					misc.println("Error saving server reports..");
				}
		}
	}
}[/code]
